mistaken: Joyce’s Irishness is intrinsic to his modernism, informing his most distinctive literary experiments. Ireland, Gibbons shows, is not just a source of subject matter or content for Joyce, but of form itself. Joyce’s stylistic innovations can be traced at least as much to the tragedies of Irish history as to the shock of European modernity, as he explores the incomplete project of inner life under colonialism. Joyce’s language, Gibbons reveals, is haunted by ghosts, less concerned with the stream of consciousness than with a vernacular interior dialogue, the “shout in the street,” that gives room to outside voices and shadowy presences, the disruptions of a late colonial culture in crisis. Showing us how memory under modernism breaks free of the nightmare of history, and how in doing so it gives birth to new forms, Gibbons forces us to think anew about Joyce’s achievement and its foundations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aModernism (Literature)zIreland. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aireland, modernism, folklore, nationalism, memory, community, commemoration, irishness, national identity, rebellion, patriotism, form, history, colonialism, england, great britain, stream of consciousness, ghosts, haunting, legacy, dublin, self, city, free indirect discourse, vernacular, subjectivity, spectre, supernatural, premonition, dead, death, nonfiction, literature, classics, criticism, literary movements, nation, wandering rocks, bloom.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226236209423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226236209/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGru